Use the quotient rule for exponents: when dividing like bases, subtract the exponents.

For the p-terms  
p^{−4} / p^{2} = p^{−4−2} = p^{−6}

For the q-terms  
q^{2} / q^{−3} = q^{2−(−3)} = q^{2+3} = q^{5}

Combine the results:  
p^{−6} q^{5}

Convert the negative exponent to a positive one:  
q^{5} / p^{6}

So,  
(p^{−4} q^{2}) / (p^{2} q^{−3}) = q^{5} / p^{6}.

